This paper deals with the recognition of human-object interactions from RGB-D videos, which is a task related to computer vision (cs.CV). The paper proposes a self-organizing neural network architecture, which involves learning prototypical representations of body motion patterns and objects, accounting for the development of action-object mappings in an unsupervised fashion. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also mentions the use of Grow-When-Required (GWR) networks, which are a type of neural network architecture (cs.NE). Finally, the paper deals with the recognition of actions in natural environments, which suggests that it could also be relevant to robotics (cs.RO).
